   [12]Melissa Nobles
   Chancellor

                             Our successes together

   March 08, 2022

Highlights

     o MIT's partnership with the GSC and other student representatives has
       led to many substantive improvements for graduate students over the
       past five years.
     o MIT's stipend increases have outpaced those at nearly all private
       universities with graduate student unions.
     o MIT has invested in students with the most pressing needs, allocating
       more funds for those with families, those on short-term appointments,
       and those in need of longer-term support.
     o MIT has provided enhanced health and wellness support, and MIT Medical
       continues to offer excellent, low-cost, robust health insurance
       options.
     o MIT has championed its international students, helping them to weather
       the pandemic and stepping up to protect them against challenges from
       shifting federal immigration policies.
     o MIT has worked directly with students to build a more inclusive,
       supportive, and diverse community; expand support networks for
       graduate students; combat harassment; and foster the personal and
       professional growth of its students.


   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   To MIT graduate students:

   By now you may have seen additional details on the upcoming NLRB-run
   election, on April 4 and 5, to determine whether some of MIT's graduate
   students will form a union associated with the [13]United Electrical,
   Radio and Machine Workers of America (UE). More information is available
   at [14]grad-union.mit.edu.

   Whatever the outcome of this election, all of us who lead MIT will
   continue to support every one of our extraordinarily talented students.
   Like every institution, we will always have room for improvement. Those of
   us who have devoted our lives to MIT, and to making it a place of
   excellence and belonging for generations of our students, are deeply aware
   that we must always strive to do better. We respect and admire all of our
   graduate students, and are committed to ensuring that each of you thrives
   during your time here.

   Indeed, it is our deep interest in your work and success that has led us
   to embrace roles in student support and academic life, rather than
   focusing solely on our teaching and research. And it's why we're invested
   in strengthening MIT's uniquely effective collaboration with its student
   leaders -- an approach that has been advocated by the Institute's student
   community, is in keeping with MIT's spirit and values, and informs MIT's
   work to create a more caring and supportive environment for everyone.

   Over the past five years, our direct partnership with graduate student
   leaders, including the Graduate Student Council (GSC) and other
   representatives, has led to many substantive improvements for graduate
   students, including:

     o Greater financial security for all students: MIT's
       cost-of-living-based stipend increases -- part of a process led by the
       GSC -- have outpaced those at nearly all private universities with
       graduate student unions. Throughout the pandemic, MIT offered its
       students generous assistance with housing costs, moving expenses, and
       other financial burdens.
     o MIT has invested in students with the most pressing needs: The
       Institute has introduced new programs through which we have allocated
       approximately $1 million in grants for graduate students with
       families, students on short-term appointments, and doctoral students
       needing longer-term support.
     o MIT has provided enhanced health and wellness support: MIT Medical
       continues to offer excellent, robust [15]health insurance options with
       premiums that are [16]on par with or less expensive than our peers,
       and has expanded copay-free access to behavioral health care outside
       of MIT Medical from 12 visits to 52 visits per year.
     o MIT has championed its international students: In 2020, MIT joined
       with Harvard University in [17]successfully filing suit against the US
       Department of Homeland Security to rescind a federal policy that would
       have barred international students on F-1 visas from taking a full
       online course load while studying in the United States. And to help
       manage the challenges that the pandemic presented for its
       international graduate students, MIT allocated $5.8 million to
       facilitate roughly 1,300 remote international appointments. This
       ensured that students did not face interruptions to their academic and
       research progress, and were able to continue their studies and
       research from abroad.
     o MIT has worked to build a more inclusive, supportive, and diverse
       community: It has [18]hired school-based diversity deans; increased
       staffing in the [19]International Students Office, [20]Career Advising
       and Professional Development, and [21]GradSupport; added an employee
       to provide dedicated support for veterans and [22]created a Grad
       Families Office; invested [23]additional resources in its Violence
       Prevention and Response and Institute Discrimination and Harassment
       Response (IDHR) offices; refined [24]anti-retaliation policies;
       implemented a new [25]guaranteed transitional funding program for
       students who change research advisors or groups; and offered
       additional [26]mentoring and harassment-prevention training.
     o MIT has fostered students' personal and professional growth: It has
       enhanced advising and training, offering more than 40 workshops and
       panels in partnership with 15 academic and administrative departments
       and developing more focused career fairs and networking opportunities.


   As we draw closer to the election on April 4-5, this is the time for you
   to become as informed as possible. Learn about the unionization process
   and what it might mean for you, so that you can cast an informed vote.
   Critically assess the positions of [27]MIT's leadership -- including our
   [28]responses to recent claims made by union supporters -- as well as
   those of the [29]MIT graduate students who are opposed to the UE, and the
   members of the [30]MIT Graduate Student Union, who are working with the
   UE.

   It is essential that every eligible student make it a priority to vote on
   April 4-5. This election's outcome will be determined by a simple majority
   of those who vote, but will be binding on both voters and non-voters in
   the [31]proposed bargaining unit.

   Sincerely,

   Melissa Nobles
   Chancellor

   Ian A. Waitz
   Vice Chancellor for Undergraduate and Graduate Education

