    1. [14]Home
    2. MIT***s position statement on why fellows shouldn***t be included in
       the UE***s proposed bargaining unit

MIT***s position statement on why fellows shouldn***t be included in the UE***s
                            proposed bargaining unit

   MIT***s senior leadership does not believe that unionization is the most
   constructive path forward for our graduate students, and have shared their
   concerns in [15]recent letters to the graduate student body.

   The following statement explains why they do not think students with full
   MIT fellowship awards should be part of the bargaining unit proposed by
   the United Electrical, Radio and Machine Workers (UE). It also addresses
   several inaccuracies and omitted facts in the recent [16]Tech op-ed titled
   ***MIT***s administration seeks to exclude over 1,000 graduate workers on
   fellowship from unionization vote.***

   The main points are:

     o Applying a union labor process to a student body requires drawing
       lines between groups of students
     o The UE was the first to exclude over 2,000 students from its proposed
       bargaining unit, including students on full external fellowships
     o MIT***s current inclusive, collaborative, flexible model *** which
       supports ALL students *** is more responsive to individual students***
       needs and allows MIT to maintain important program-to-program
       differences across 108 unique masters and doctoral degree programs
     o Being in the bargaining unit could strip fellows of the flexibility
       and certain benefits they currently enjoy**

All students have academic relationships with MIT; not all have employment
relationships

   Graduate student unionization involves a labor bargaining process that is
   fundamentally about negotiating the ***terms and conditions of
   employment.*** While many graduate students have an employment
   relationship with MIT, many do not. All students have an academic
   relationship with MIT. But only student-employees can organize and become
   part of a labor union.**

   This is one of the principal reasons why the Institute***s senior leaders
   think that our current collaborative, holistic, flexible, and nimble model
   for working with all graduate students *** a model that cuts across both
   their employment and academic relationships *** is the better one for
   being responsive to individual students*** needs and for enabling MIT to
   maintain many important program-to-program differences across our 108
   unique masters and doctoral degree programs.

The UE has already excluded over 2,000 graduate students from the proposed
bargaining unit**

   Unionization requires determining who is and isn***t an employee under
   federal labor law. Because of that requirement, the UE was the first to
   exclude over 2,000 graduate students from the proposed bargaining unit
   when they filed their petition with the National Labor Relations Board
   (NLRB) on February 1, 2022.

   The UE dropped students who receive full fellowship support from external
   sources (e.g., certain awards from US federal agencies, foreign government
   agencies, corporations, or foundations) and those who are otherwise
   self-funded. These students conduct research and teaching as required by
   their academic programs, just like students who receive fellowship awards
   from MIT.

   The reason the UE did this is because they do not believe students who are
   on externally supported fellowships or who are self-funded are employees
   who can unionize under NLRB rules. MIT***s senior leaders agree. But the
   Institute***s leadership also believes that MIT internal fellows fall into
   that same non-employee category.

   Ultimately, drawing unnecessary lines between groups of students ***
   including some while excluding others *** is inconsistent with MIT***s
   values. The reason it is happening is because the UE is applying a union
   labor process to a student body.**

Asking the NLRB to confirm that fellows are not employees under federal rules

   The NLRB has ruled that a graduate student is an employee and eligible to
   unionize if the university:

     o Pays the student;
     o Directs and controls the student***s work; and**
     o Requires specific services be performed as a condition of receiving
       their funding.

   MIT***s senior leaders [17]do not believe that students on full fellowship
   appointments are employees under this rule and are asking the NLRB to
   confirm that.

   It***s worth noting that MIT is not alone in seeing a distinction between
   graduate fellows and student-workers. The graduate student union at the
   University of Iowa *** the only graduate student union affiliated with the
   UE *** does not include fellows. The same is true at Brown University and
   the University of Massachusetts.

Comparing TA/RA appointments with internal fellowships and external funding

   The below table illustrates the similarities and key differences between
   appointment and award types at MIT.

   In short, students on MIT fellowship awards are most akin to students on
   full external fellowships, and the UE has already excluded the latter
   group from their proposed bargaining unit because they do not view them as
   student employees.**

   RAs and TAs, unlike fellows and self-funded students, are generally
   required to perform specific services, or work on specific research
   projects, in order to receive their assistantship funding. This ***pay for
   services rendered*** is at the core of what it means to be an employee
   under federal labor law.**

                                TA  RA  MIT Fellowship External
                                                       Fellowship/Self-Funded
   Take required courses        Yes Yes Yes            Yes
   Conduct research for         Yes Yes Yes            Yes
   thesis**
   Provide specific services,
   or work on certain research  Yes Yes No             No
   projects, in order to
   receive funding**
   Can lose funding for
   unsatisfactory academic      Yes Yes Yes            Yes
   performance
   Can lose funding for
   unsatisfactory performance   Yes Yes No             No
   of service requirements
   Funding controlled by PI     No  Yes No             No
   Verify employment
   eligibility through I-9      Yes Yes No             No
   forms
   Receive W-2s from MIT for    Yes Yes No             No
   employment income**
   Stipend and tuition is
   charged to federal research  N/A Yes No             No
   contracts and grants
   Included in UE***s Proposed  Yes Yes Yes            No
   Bargaining Unit

   (Note: some departments also have non-service RAs that function more like
   MIT internal fellowships).

Why is being outside of the bargaining unit better for students on MIT
fellowships?

   Fellowship awards are our [18]most flexible form of financial assistance
   because they do not come with service requirements beyond the very
   rigorous academic expectations required of all students. This is why
   fellowships are regarded as the most attractive form of funding by
   students across the world when they consider admission decisions and why
   fellowships are often awarded early in a student***s academic progression.

   It is also why fellowships are frequently awarded in MIT***s
   [19]Guaranteed Transitional Support Program when students want to change
   research groups *** explicitly to remove any service requirements.

   MIT***s international students who are awarded fellowships also depend on
   the flexibility (and income) they provide, especially those with spouses
   or partners who cannot work. That***s because federal immigration law
   limits on-campus employment opportunities for international students to 20
   hours per week during the fall and spring semesters. International
   students on full RA and TA appointments are not permitted to take on other
   on-campus employment opportunities during these terms. If fellowships are
   deemed to require services and included in the bargaining unit, then
   international students awarded full fellowships would be subject to the
   same employment restrictions as RAs and TAs.**

   In short, in a unionized setting, some of the flexibility fellows
   currently enjoy would likely be eliminated. This is why, if the
   unionization effort is ultimately successful, MIT***s senior leaders think
   it is better for students with fellowship awards not to be included in the
   bargaining unit.
   **

   MIT has created this website to help every graduate student cast an
   informed vote on whether or not to form a union affiliated with the United
   Electrical, Radio & Machine Workers of America.**

   No one can cast an informed vote if they hear only one side of the story.
   MIT trusts its students to think for themselves, ask questions, discuss
   issues, and make decisions based on complete and accurate information.

